-- Japan, India, Malaysia, Thailand, Singapore: Asian Bond, Currency Preview
-- Lilian Karunungan
-- 2010-06-13T22:40:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-13/japan-india-malaysia-thailand-singapore-asian-bond-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku will hold a
media briefing at 11 a.m. in Tokyo and another press briefing
at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The Bank of Japan will start a two-day policy board
meeting at which it will leave the policy rate unchanged at 0.1
percent, according to a Bloomberg News survey.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.23 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest inter-dealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 91.71 per dollar at 7:30 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: Financial markets will be closed for three days
from June 14 for the Dragon Boat holidays. Ten-year yields were
at 3.3 percent, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The
yuan was at 6.8323 per dollar.  
 India: The benchmark wholesale-price index advanced 9.60
percent in May after a 9.59 percent gain in the previous month,
according to the median estimate of economists in a Bloomberg
News survey before the data today.  
 The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.57
percent. The rupee was at 46.85.  
 South Korea: The Bank of Korea will report export and
import prices for May. Export prices fell 6.7 percent in April
from a year earlier, while import prices rose 5.1 percent.  
 The yield on the 5.75 percent debt due September 2018 was
4.94 percent. The won was at 1,246.10.  
 Malaysia: The government will sell 2.5 billion ringgit
($762 million) of 10-year Islamic bonds today, according to
data published by the central bank on its website. The
government will separately offer more of the June 2020 Shariah-
compliant notes in a private sale to investors at the same time,
according to its sale calendar.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent note due November 2019 was
4.08 percent. The ringgit was at 3.2790.  
 Philippines: Local financial markets and government
offices are shut today for a holiday. Trading and work will
resume on June 15.  
 The yield on 7.75 percent securities due February 2020 was
8.08 percent, according to the Philippine Dealing & Exchange
Corp. The peso was at 46.478.  
 Thailand: The government will sell 2 billion baht ($62
million) of 28-day and 4 billion baht each of 91- and 182-day
bills.  
 The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in June 2019
was 3.25 percent. The baht was at 32.49.  
